Patch Set 1:

Struggling to get this to work:

$ curl -k -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" -X POST https://${BMC_IP}/redfish/v1/UpdateService/Actions/UpdateService.SimpleUpdate -d '{"TransferProtocol":"TFTP", "ImageURI":"192.168.0.1/hello.txt"}'
{
  "ImageURI@Message.ExtendedInfo": [
    {
      "@odata.type": "/redfish/v1/$metadata#Message.v1_0_0.Message",
      "Message": "The property ImageURI is not in the list of valid properties for the resource.",
      "MessageArgs": [
        "ImageURI"
      ],
      "MessageId": "Base.1.4.0.PropertyUnknown",
      "Resolution": "Remove the unknown property from the request body and resubmit the request if the operation failed.",
      "Severity": "Warning"
    }
  ],
  "error": {
    "@Message.ExtendedInfo": [
      {
        "@odata.type": "/redfish/v1/$metadata#Message.v1_0_0.Message",
        "Message": "The action UpdateService.SimpleUpdate requires the parameter TransferProtocol to be present in the request body.",
        "MessageArgs": [
          "UpdateService.SimpleUpdate",
          "TransferProtocol"
        ],
        "MessageId": "Base.1.4.0.ActionParameterMissing",
        "Resolution": "Supply the action with the required parameter in the request body when the request is resubmitted.",
        "Severity": "Critical"
      }
    ],
    "code": "Base.1.4.0.ActionParameterMissing",
    "message": "The action UpdateService.SimpleUpdate requires the parameter TransferProtocol to be present in the request body."
  }
}

I don't recommend this very often, but this might be a case where boost::split would be useful to avoid checking a bunch of redundant error conditions.

something like
std::vector<std::string> v
boost::split(v, imageURI, boost::any_of("/"));
if (c.size() != 2){
  // handle error
  return
}

On second thought... I wonder if we're supposed to use a fully qualified URL parser here to decode something like "tftp://<myserver>:<my port>/<mypath>

I need to look closer at the redfish spec.

This is going to duplicate the error messages, right?

I wonder if the std::optional pattern would give us better behavior:

std::optional<std::string> transferProtocol;
std::optional<std::string> imageURI;
std::shared_ptr<AsyncResp> asyncResp = std::make_shared<AsyncResp>(res);

BMCWEB_LOG_DEBUG << "Enter UpdateService.SimpleUpdate doPost";

if (!json_util::readJson(req, asyncResp->res, "TransferProtocol",
                        transferProtocol, "ImageURI", imageURI))
{
     BMCWEB_LOG_ERROR << "Bad simple update request";
     return;
}

if (!transferProtocol){
    messages::actionParameterMissing(asyncResp->res,
                                     "UpdateService.SimpleUpdate",
                                     "TransferProtocol");
    return
}

if (!imageURI){
    messages::actionParameterMissing(asyncResp->res,
                                     "UpdateService.SimpleUpdate",
                                     "ImageURI");
    return;
}



I'm not sure how much I really care, as we're talking about error codes, but the above might be something to consider if you're seeing duplicated errors.

It seems a little odd you're parsing this by hand.  I would've expect to just declare the TransferProtocol parameter std::optional<std::string>, then check for existence later.  Something like


std::optional<std::string> transferProtocol;
std::string imageURI;
if (!json_util::readJson(req, asyncResp->res, "TransferProtocol",
                            transferProtocol, "ImageURI", imageURI))
{
    BMCWEB_LOG_DEBUG
        << "Missing TransferProtocol or ImageURI parameter";
    return;
}


if (transferProtocol){
    // Follow option 1 logic

} else {
    // follow option 2 logic.
}

That avoids a bunch of extra lookups and code.
